ese contemporary art into a global phenomenon. Drawing on ethnographic fieldwork and experience as a videographer and curator, Welland analyzes encounters between artists, curators, officials, and urban planners as they negotiated the social role of art and built new cultural institutions. Focusing on the contradictions and exclusions that emerged, Welland traces the complex gender politics involved and shows that feminist forms of art practice hold the potential to reshape consciousness, produce a nonnormative history of Chinese contemporary art, and imagine other, more just worlds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArtzChinazBeijing. 0aArt, Chinesey21st century. 0aArt, Moderny21st century. 0aArtistszChinazBeijingy21st century. 0aGlobalization in art. 70(DE-601)1058229570(DE-588)4114333-4aKunst2gnd 70(DE-601)2387199600(DE-588)4482930-9aGeschlechterforschung2gnd 70(DE-601)3022971110(DE-588)4557997-0aGlobalisierung2gnd 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082236928840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372479/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles